+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------+-----------------------------+
|              Feature              |           malloc()          |             new             |
+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------+-----------------------------+
| Language                          | C language function         | C++ operator / keyword      |
| Purpose                           | Allocates raw memory only   | Allocates memory + creates object |
| Type Safety                       | Not type-safe (returns void*) | Type-safe (returns correct type) |
| Constructor / Destructor           | Does NOT call constructor or destructor | Calls both automatically |
| Initialization                    | Does not initialize memory  | Can initialize while creating |
| Error Handling                    | Returns NULL if fails       | Throws bad_alloc exception if fails |
| Memory Release                    | Must use free()             | Must use delete              |
| Overloading / Customization        | Cannot be overloaded        | Can be overloaded (custom memory mgmt) |
| Simplicity                        | Needs type casting and manual setup | Easier and safer in C++ |
+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------+-----------------------------+

✅ **In short:**  
- `malloc` → Just gives you empty memory (C style).  
- `new` → Gives memory **and** builds the object properly (C++ style).  
Hence, in C++, always prefer **`new`** over **`malloc`**.
